### PHP Sessions

Sessions allow you to store user information across multiple page requests.

### Starting a Session

```php
<?php
session_start(); // Must be called before any HTML output

// Set session variables
$_SESSION["username"] = "John";
$_SESSION["role"] = "admin";

echo "Session started for " . $_SESSION["username"];
?>
```

### Using Session Variables

```php
<?php
session_start();

// Check if logged in
if (isset($_SESSION["user_id"])) {
    echo "Welcome back, " . $_SESSION["username"];
} else {
    echo "Please log in";
}
?>
```

### Session Functions

| Function | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `session_start()` | Start new or resume existing session |
| `session_destroy()` | Destroy all session data |
| `session_unset()` | Unset all session variables |
| `session_id()` | Get or set the session ID |
| `session_regenerate_id()` | Regenerate session ID (security) |
| `session_status()` | Check if session is active |

### Login / Logout Example

```php
<?php
session_start();

// Login
$_SESSION["user_id"] = 123;
$_SESSION["username"] = "john_doe";

// Logout
session_unset();
session_destroy();
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Always call `session_start()` at the beginning of every page that uses sessions, before any HTML output.
